<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100774705521950></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100774705521950><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=11&mid=100774705521950>Suggested Familiar Revision</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=11&mid=100774705521950#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=126085><span id=Scholar>MentalSword</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>40 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Dec 7th 12:44 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The idea of giving Wizards familiars is an excellent one.  It's something that has been missing from the game.  I just feel that Verant has strayed a bit too far from the classic idea of a familiar.<br><br>First, and this may be wrong because it is second-hand info, but I hear that the familiars themselves are elementals.  To me, it would be more accurate to use, say, a miniature Bat model for the first Familiar, then a miniature Cat model, then miniature Drake, and then progressively larger Drakes.  These are the kinds of creatures that Wizards use for familiars. =)<br><br>Secondly, the Familiar needs to be attackable.  I understand that the familiar is not meant to be a pet and tank for the player as normal pets do.  As this is an entirely accurate stance.  But the familiar should still be able to attack, and be attacked.  Only, if the familiar is attacked by anything stronger than it is, it immediately runs to its master and attempts to stay behind him/her until it is no longer under attack.  And any mob argo'd onto a familiar should immediately switch that argo to the player, when the player is closer than the familiar, with the exception of other Wizard mobs who WILL attempt to take out a familiar knowing full well the cost to his enemy.<br><br>If a familiar dies, I agree that the Wizard's remaining mana should be drained.  But rather than suffer damage, the wizard should loose a percentage of stamina points, based on the level of the familiar.  These stamina points would slowly be regained over the base course of say one game month, with the inability to re-summon another familiar until all stamina points have been regained.  (Traditionally, familiar death causes a permanent constitution loss, I think that this temporary loss of stamina is a good EQ equivalent)<br><br>A Wizard should be able to dismiss his familiar, but only if the familiar is at full health and the dismissal should take at least 30 seconds.<br><br>Ok, those are some harsh penalties.  So who would want a familiar like this when some already think it is too hard loosing a familiar???  This brings me to my third point.  The Wizard should have the ability to &quot;take control&quot; of his familiar and see through the familiar's eyes, very much like the line of summoned eye spells.  Activating this ability should start a slow but steady mana drain, making the ability's duration proportional to the casters mana reserve.  I envision the average Wizard being able to control his first familiar for about 2 minutes.  The distance that the familiar can travel from the Wizard in this state would be determined by the level of the familiar, with increased mana drain at greater distances.  When the Wizard runs out of mana, or stops the ability, the familiar begins to return to it's master.  Of course, the wizard is completely oblivious to his surroundings while controlling his familiar, and could be killed without ever knowing it.  If the familiar is killed while the Wizard is controlling it, there may also be an temporary Intelligence loss along with the stamina hit.  The familiar may even be able to gather small items and bring them back.  I'm not sure if or how that could be worked out.<br><br>I think that these changes will make the Familiar concept more accurate within the game, and it makes the whole thing a bit more interesting than just an innate mana generator.  =)<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Dec  7 12:46:24 2001</em><br>&nbsp;<br>-Maintaining the Honor of Test</td></tr>
