	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok, these all seem like excellent Ideas, but....<br><br>First, have you given any thought as to the difficulty of the code and how they effect the current interface?  <br><br>Second, these are to &quot;make the Familiar concept more accurate within the game.&quot;  Ok, but accurate compared to what?  Accuracy means you are comparing to something.  Comepared to D&amp;D?  If you are comparing to D&amp;D then this would actually NOT be more accurate.  In D&amp;D at NO TIME can the master use his familiar's senses except for in a very very vague way.  His own senses are *sometimes* hightened (dependant on type of familiar).  Some familiars in D&amp;D give the master an extra ability.  This I think would be relatively easy to code into the game and an interesting side to Familiars.  As to not taking damage when your familiar dies...again this would actually make it LESS accurate by the D&amp;D standard.  In D&amp;D you lose HALF, I repeat HALF, of your hit points for weeks until you over come the system shock of the loss.  I think just loosing half your mana, and sometimes some damagae (as is the case currently with the EQ familiars) is actually being quite easy on Wizards.  The ability to take control of your familiar is also extremely against D&amp;D rules.  I could go on....<br><br>To sum up what I'm trying to point out.  These Ideas all sound wonderful when you look at them, but if you compare them to other abilities of other classes.  I think increased mana regen, decreased resistance of spells cast, etc, are all great things added to an already wonderful class.<br><br>Peace and happy Nuking to all.<br>&nbsp;<br>Slogha Kovar<br></td></tr>
