	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well my friend, you may wish to brush up on your D&amp;D...  Those sound like some old rules, although I may be the one out of date as I admittedly have not purchased a players guide in several years.  I do, however, know that current AD&amp;D requires a permanent constitution loss as a result of familiar death (reference Baulder's Gate or other current AD&amp;D based game).  Those &quot;half&quot; hit points you repeatedly mention would be a direct result of a decrease in constitution, you're primary HP stat.  Not to mention the fact that D&amp;D is an open rules game in which game-play can vary drastically from one DM to another, which really makes it impossible to directly quote any D&amp;D rule.<br><br>As far as the technical concerns go, I did give thought to programming these abilities, hence my uncertainty about gathering items with the familiar.  The scouting ability is modeled after the summoned eye spells, which currently exist, so I can see no major problems there...<br><br>And yes, you cannot make a comparison without something to compare to.  But I did not choose D&amp;D alone.  I am comparing to the IDEA of a familiar as portrayed in many fantasy games, books, movies, etc.  Of course these will all differ from one another, depending on whose creation you're referencing.  But one consistency has nearly always been a Wizard's ability to scout with their familiar.  Sometimes the Wizard tells the familiar where to go and uses telepathy to know what the familiar sees, the description returned takes into account what the familiar is capable of understanding (AD&amp;D style).  Other times, the Wizard controls the mind of the familiar directly (more commonly found in novels).  These are the kinds of things that will vary from one person's idea to another, but the general idea of scouting remains consistent regardless of the particulars of how it is carried out.<br><br>All of this discussion is moot though, as VI is quite happy with the current familiar model and not interested in changing it.<br><br>I appreciate your comments and enjoy the debate.  =)<br><br>Happy hunting!<br><br>&nbsp;<br>-Maintaining the Honor of Test</td></tr>
